Those are the two apps that Birdsong apps has published.

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.180
The other hat I'm wearing today is for Eurosky,

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:31.730
and that's what I want to talk to you about today

00:01:31.730 --> 00:01:31.980
.

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:37.680
For the next slide, content warning, disturbing image.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:39.840
Children, maybe cover her eyes.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:42.110
SEBASTIAN VOGELSANG: This

00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:44.860
is from January 25.

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:45.080
SEBASTIAN VOGELSANG: Yes

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:45.140
.

00:01:45.170 --> 00:01:45.450
SEBASTIAN VOGELSANG: For

00:01:45.460 --> 00:01:48.370
those of you not familiar, this is Bezos, Zucker

00:01:48.370 --> 00:01:50.180
berg, Pichai, Musk.

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:52.120
SEBASTIAN VOGELSANG: Does

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:54.120
anybody know where this is?

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:54.860
SEBASTIAN VOGELSANG: Probably

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:55.420
, right?

00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:56.100
OK.

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:59.440
So this is the front row at Trump's inauguration.

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:03.940
And in the weeks that followed this event, a lot of

00:02:03.950 --> 00:02:06.860
these platforms took drastic decisions.

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:10.920
Meta ended its fact-checking.

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:13.370
So basically, on this day, Big Tech, they didn

00:02:13.370 --> 00:02:15.110
't just comply with stuff.

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:18.980
They basically raced to the front of the room.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:24.600
And since then, the US administration has increasingly targeted independent media

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:24.940
.

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:30.000
And with X, this had already been started two years at

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.660
this point, being used as a political instrument, not only

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:37.320
in the US, but also in Europe, where Musk tried

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:41.240
to influence elections, not only in Germany, but I think

00:02:41.270 --> 00:02:43.180
also in Hungary.

00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:46.500
And we need to ask ourselves, when Musk acquired Twitter,

00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:48.810
what was actually captured here?

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:49.700
SEBASTIAN VOGELSANG: It

00:02:49.710 --> 00:02:50.320
wasn't a company.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.040
And it wasn't an algorithm.

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:53.740
It was actually infrastructure.

00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:58.090
The pipes that your media and your journalism runs on, the

00:02:58.090 --> 00:03:01.620
identity layer, the distribution layer, the moderation layer, all

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:05.110
captured overnight by one acquisition.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:07.300
When you look at companies like X, this is what the

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:08.260
stack currently looks like.

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:10.510
You have identity storage.

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:12.000
You have distribution.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:13.810
You have moderation.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:15.840
You have apps and interfaces.

00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:18.410
And when you combine all this in one company, in one

00:03:18.490 --> 00:03:20.160
stack, that's not just an app.

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:22.100
That's infrastructure with a product on top.

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:27.970
And try to democratically govern this right now.

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:34.060
Identity verification, ranking, advertiser relationships, speech rights

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:37.820
across jurisdictions, moderation appeals, data privacy, et cetera,

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:41.340
all at once, all in one place.

00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:43.650
And the complexity is actually the point here.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:47.490
The monolith protects itself by being too tangled to just regulate

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:47.660
.

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:51.240
And we see this in Europe right now on an everyday basis

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:55.340
where the EU government tries to regulate big tech and just can

00:03:55.370 --> 00:03:56.600
't.

00:03:56.680 --> 00:04:00.300
Thinking back to Trump's inauguration, you now have this

00:04:00.410 --> 00:04:04.330
concentrated, unaccountable power over public discourse.

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:05.230
And we've seen it.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:07.360
And we've watched it happen again.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.060
And my wife told me not to make this reference.

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:10.870
But I'm from Germany.

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:13.920
And this matters to me.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:23.280
Sorry, so what does democratic infrastructure actually look like?

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:26.100
Well, it turns out we sort of have an answer to

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:28.920
this from another area.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:30.860
And that's public broadcasting.

00:04:30.940 --> 00:04:35.140
What you see here is a map of national media landscape in

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:39.430
Germany after World War II, in which the regional broadcas

00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:43.440
ters had all been merged into one national network by the Nazis

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:45.570
to create a powerful means of propaganda.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:52.700
The allies insisted on a decentralized independent structure for German public broadcasting

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:52.960
.

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:58.120
They created these regional public broadcasting agencies that, by and large

00:04:58.120 --> 00:04:59.520
, still exist today.

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:04.080
All these services are mainly financed through license fees paid by

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:05.960
every household in Germany.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:12.180
And they are governed by councils of representatives of the socially relevant

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:12.960
groups.

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:16.730
And Catherine will be happy to talk to you about that if

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:18.670
you want to know more.

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:22.600
Because she has been doing that for years.

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:27.220
So what was built here is infrastructure that cannot be captured by

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:29.170
government or by money.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:33.300
And we need to do that again for social media.

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:35.890
When we think about-- I stole this from Robin, by

00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:36.520
the way.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:39.840
When we think about social media, we usually have the wrong

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:40.920
mental model.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.800
We usually think it's like this, everybody's happy,

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:46.900
social media apps are like fun, and we can just like

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:48.500
post memes on them.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:52.300
But the actual right model analogy is this, it's roads

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:52.540
.

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:53.800
They're hard to replace.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:55.740
They have many downstream users.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:06:00.170
And whoever owns these roads sets the rules for everyone on them

00:06:00.170 --> 00:06:00.820
.

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:04.740
So the people owning these rules have the durable power over everything

00:06:04.840 --> 00:06:05.570
that moves on them.

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:12.400
You all, or most of you, have knowledge of the

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:15.480
protocol that we're talking about at this conference, the AT

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:16.080
O protocol.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.210
And you know what the pieces are.

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:21.080
And you also know how open protocols like ATProto let

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:25.580
you operate these components independently of each other, thus guaranteeing

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:28.380
that there will be not too much power in one corner,

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:30.690
right?

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:34.700
And I've witnessed this empowerment myself last year when I built

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:37.540
the app I talked about, Flashes, which is sort

00:06:37.630 --> 00:06:40.130
of a visual social media on ATProto.

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:42.300
Some say it's an Instagram clone.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:46.820
I was able to take advantage-- screw those people, right

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:47.000
?

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:53.480
I was able to take advantage of BlueSky's existing

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:54.620
infrastructure here.

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:58.160
And thus, I didn't have to rebuild identity, social

00:06:58.160 --> 00:06:59.240
graph, distribution.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:02.560
And I could just focus on the user experience.

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:06.190
But when it came to the stuff that wasn't covered by

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.890
BlueSky or their app view, like moderation for my

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:13.060
own custom lexicons in there, I either had the

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:16.660
choice to build this on my own, put money in it

00:07:16.690 --> 00:07:21.190
, raise capital, or actually do it the protocol way and

00:07:21.310 --> 00:07:24.700
get together with people and find a common solution that everybody can

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:25.430
use.

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:30.840
And luckily, I chose the latter and joined forces with Ivan

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:34.690
and Robin and Sharif, who were previously working on Free

00:07:34.690 --> 00:07:35.200
R feeds.

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:37.440
I don't know if you talked about this, but it

00:07:37.450 --> 00:07:41.420
was an initiative that set out last year to promote ATPr

00:07:41.420 --> 00:07:43.540
oto outside of the realm of the inner BlueSky ecosystem

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:43.600
.

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:50.480
And this is how Eurosky and the model foundation got founded

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:50.920
.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.960
Eurosky isn't an app or a platform.

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:57.720
It's not a competitor to anything you're building here.

00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:00.840
It's shared infrastructure for the ATProto ecosystem.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.680
It's operated in Europe, under EU law, and we

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:08.300
're aiming at providing developers, like myself, with the same

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:11.240
benefits that I got to enjoy when I built on the back

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:13.440
of BlueSky's infrastructure.

00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:16.190
Like right now, we're providing PDSs, rel

00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:19.010
ays, we're working on agnostic app views and

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:24.360
moderation pipelines, and all that as European commons, not

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:30.200
as a US commercial product.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:32.880
So here's why we think it's necessary for Europe.

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:35.360
We like to say we can just build things, but this

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:38.680
is what happens when you just build things in Europe.

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:42.600
We got this the first week after we unofficially launched

00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:46.100
our PDS, and it reads to the privacy officer under

00:08:46.190 --> 00:08:50.500
Article 15 of the General Data Protection Regulation, GDPR

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:53.280
, I am requesting a copy of all personal data you hold

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:56.260
about me associated with this email address.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:09:01.420
Please provide me the information in a commonly used electronic format with

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:05.000
a statutory one-month period.

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:09.560
And as a developer, you can either try to handle this

00:09:09.560 --> 00:09:12.940
on your own, and if you know the GDPR,

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:15.980
you're probably able to do this, but there are already

00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:19.230
a lot of apps out there that just don't deploy to

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:22.360
Europe because they are afraid of this.

00:09:22.440 --> 00:09:25.400
So you either know how to handle this or you just skip

00:09:25.470 --> 00:09:26.280
Europe.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:30.120
I mean, obviously, you should not save too much data

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:32.780
for the clients that you provide.

00:09:32.860 --> 00:09:36.190
You shouldn't like lock IP addresses if it's not necessary

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:39.840
, but this is something that I myself had to like learn

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:44.420
over years dealing with GDPR because this also didn't happen

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:46.400
overnight in Europe.

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:47.400
Right?

00:09:47.480 --> 00:09:51.370
So, of course, where your infrastructure runs determines what laws

00:09:51.370 --> 00:09:52.240
apply to it.

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:55.550
So GDPR, DSA, data residency with Eur

00:09:55.550 --> 00:10:00.450
osky, this will all be handled at the infrastructure layer

00:10:00.450 --> 00:10:00.780
.

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:03.080
So you just build your app, and we handle the compliance

00:10:03.190 --> 00:10:07.930
, plumbing, and give you the European market actually at scale

00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:11.860
without routing data through the US.

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:15.110
Talking about the stack, we just soft launched our PDS

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:15.400
.

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:21.180
We worked through the preregistration list, and we

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:25.490
're almost at 2,000-- oh, no, 9

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.600
,000 users migrate.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:31.040
I think we're by now the largest third-party PD

00:10:31.050 --> 00:10:34.340
S in the atmosphere except for the bridging PDS for

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:41.070
the Fediverse, and we managed to do this within two

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:42.420
weeks.

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:44.420
Why isn't this-- two weeks?

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:46.400
Yeah.

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:53.820
This was with invites only, like with invite codes, so

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:56.930
it's not even publicly launched yet.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:01.050
We managed to pull this off by implementing our own migration tool

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:06.540
, and we called it EU Hall.

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:11.530
Thank you.

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:12.540
Why?

00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:14.540
Why?

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:18.520
We're ready to rename it at any time.

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:22.500
So the thing is, when we ran tests with the existing

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:26.530
tools out there, which are awesome-- I want to put

00:11:26.590 --> 00:11:29.490
this down-- Bailey built PDSMover, which is

00:11:29.490 --> 00:11:33.120
a phenomenal tool-- but we saw drop-off rates of

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:35.540
up to 50% with the users we tested it with,

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:39.250
and not because the existing migration solution isn't bad or anything

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:42.350
, but because we're actually dealing with non-tech-

00:11:42.350 --> 00:11:45.340
savvy users, right, that are used to starting

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:49.920
processes and closing their window or closing the laptop when they started

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:51.030
it, and then the migration fails.

00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:56.030
So we decided to ship something server-based that would continue

00:11:56.030 --> 00:11:59.980
running in the background, while not invading your privacy more

00:11:59.980 --> 00:12:01.040
than necessary.

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:05.020
For example, we encrypt the tokens that we generate for

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:09.040
the transfer during the migration, delete them right after.

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:12.630
We're all GDPR-conformant, so yeah

00:12:12.630 --> 00:12:13.020
.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:16.040
I think it worked pretty well.

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:18.040
So that was EU Hall.

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:21.040
Now to something that we'd like to premiere here today.

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:23.040
This isn't public yet?

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:24.040
Yeah.

00:12:24.120 --> 00:12:26.040
One more thing.

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:30.150
Like I said, we're not trying to be the next

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:35.310
Twitter or X for Europe, but rather a portal to the

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:36.040
atmosphere.

00:12:36.120 --> 00:12:39.590
So to reflect that, Emilia, who I'm saying

00:12:39.610 --> 00:12:43.740
hi to on stream, she's in Berlin, who most

00:12:43.810 --> 00:12:46.350
of you know from the ecosystem, has built something for us

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:48.850
that we're going to be launching really soon, and that

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:52.020
will let anyone experience what this ecosystem is about.

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:55.040
It will look something like this.

00:12:55.120 --> 00:13:01.720
This will be Eurosky's portal site, so

00:13:01.850 --> 00:13:06.030
you can either create your Eurosky account there.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:10.930
We'll let users set up new accounts without going through the

00:13:10.930 --> 00:13:14.040
usual apps, so they can do it right there.

00:13:14.120 --> 00:13:17.040
We'll get rid of the invite codes.

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:21.020
You can obviously just log into your accounts.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:25.180
Goes without saying, given that Emilia worked on it,

00:13:25.180 --> 00:13:28.040
it's relying 100% on OAuth.

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:33.260
And this is what it will look like for now when onboard

00:13:33.310 --> 00:13:34.040
ing.

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:39.560
As you will see, we are not going to give you

00:13:39.570 --> 00:13:45.380
our own content there, but we will rather feature all the

00:13:45.560 --> 00:13:48.040
applications that are active on the atmosphere.

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:52.940
So all of your applications will be in that board, so

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:57.500
people can jump right into any of these applications and will start

00:13:57.710 --> 00:13:59.040
featuring applications.

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:01.110
Of course, since it's Eurosky, we

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:03.040
'll have like a European section to feature European apps.

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:08.030
But essentially, we're trying to give people access, fast

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:11.220
access, quick access to the tools that are already out there

00:14:11.220 --> 00:14:13.040
, instead of trying to build our own.

00:14:13.120 --> 00:14:19.040
So we hope by doing this and explaining what each app is

00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:22.100
and what it does, that we'll get more traction to

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:23.040
these apps.

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:31.030
Oh, thank you.

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:33.040
A little preview of what's coming afterwards.

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:37.020
We're currently setting up a PLC mirror and a relay

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:41.520
, and that should be ready to go in the coming weeks

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:42.040
.

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:44.980
Next on our list would be an app view, very much

